My thanks to 
@esenechal https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/902480
@Deelou https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/902422
who have explained and summed up the situation as I understand it to be, but, interestingly, have made significantly different forecasts! This forecast of mine is partially strategic.  Since the vote to hold a GE could happen in just a few days, closing this question, my forecast for a GE is higher than I think it really is.  I actually think that extending A50 is more likely.   I've made 24 forecasts on this question to date!  There's no way I'm going to score well, but I sure have learned a lot! EDIT:  @Emil has challenged me in the most polite way about the wisdom of strategic forecasting.  I know that in the GJ training materials they say that it is unwise to do this.  Emil presented me with a logical argument that I even could follow . . . but . . . . it seems counter-intuitive to me to not increase my forecast for a GE when it could be set in the next 4 days, when the other options either couldn't occur in that time-frame (the 3 leave options) or are extremely unlikely to happen in the next 4 days (revoke or set a date for a referendum since legislation to do either has not been submitted).  Even extend A50 is extremely unlikely to occur in the next 4-5 days because it hasn't been requested and the 27 EU countries do not have a meeting scheduled.   If a vote to set a date for a GE passes on Monday, when I knew it was on the agenda, and many analysts said it might, wouldn't I regret not having adjusted my forecast upwards for set a date?  I sure would!  If the vote fails, then I'll decrease my forecast.  Yes, my Brier score will suffer if I'm wrong (duh!) , but I won't feel as foolish about that as I would if I didn't adjust my forecast upwards for a GE today.  I'm willing to take the risk of being wrong for 4 days because maybe I'll be right. I invite others to try to convince me that strategic forecasting like this on this question is an unwise thing to do, if you can do so without calling me an idiot or fool.
